pomProject.name: Apache Commons BeanUtils
pomProject.description: Apache Commons BeanUtils provides an easy-to-use but flexible wrapper around reflection and introspection.

pomProject.name: Apache Commons CLI
pomProject.description: Apache Commons CLI provides a simple API for presenting, processing, and validating a Command Line Interface.

pomProject.name: Apache Commons Collections
pomProject.description: Types that extend and augment the Java Collections Framework.

pomProject.name: Apache Commons Configuration
pomProject.description: Tools to assist in the reading of configuration/preferences files in various formats; requires Java 8.

pomProject.name: Apache Commons Lang
pomProject.description: Apache Commons Lang, a package of Java utility classes for the classes that are in java.lang's hierarchy, or are considered to be so standard as to justify existence in java.lang. The code is tested using the latest revision of the JDK for supported LTS releases: 8, 11, 17 and 21 currently. See https://github.com/apache/commons-lang/blob/master/.github/workflows/maven.yml Please ensure your build environment is up-to-date and kindly report any build issues.

pomProject.name: Apache Commons Logging
pomProject.description: Apache Commons Logging is a thin adapter allowing configurable bridging to other, well-known logging systems.

pomProject.name: Apache Commons Net
pomProject.description: Apache Commons Net library contains a collection of network utilities and protocol implementations. Supported protocols include Echo, Finger, FTP, NNTP, NTP, POP3(S), SMTP(S), Telnet, and Whois.

pomProject.name: Apache Commons Text
pomProject.description: Apache Commons Text is a set of utility functions and reusable components for the purpose of processing and manipulating text that should be of use in a Java environment.

pomProject.name: JSON in Java
pomProject.description: JSON is a light-weight, language independent, data interchange format. See http://www.JSON.org/ The files in this package implement JSON encoders/decoders in Java. It also includes the capability to convert between JSON and XML, HTTP headers, Cookies, and CDL. This is a reference implementation. There are a large number of JSON packages in Java. Perhaps someday the Java community will standardize on one. Until then, choose carefully.
